That said, there are times when leverage can be useful:

When trading LTF and you want to have more than one position open you will need to use some leverage to have margin to open more positions) but by then you will know how to use it.

(6/6) 🧵

High leverage and cross mode is the fastest way to bust an account.

Forget leverage, all you have to do is:

> Decide how much $$$ to risk on each trade (say $100).
> And then calculate what size you need to risk only $100 regardless of setup and distance to stop loss.

(5/6) 🧵

But this is not all. If the trader uses the "isolated" mode, the liquidation will only affect the margin used to open the position.

That is to say;

If the trader uses $10 with x100 leverage, only $10 will be liquidated.

But if the trader uses "cross" mode, the liquidation will… https://t.co/FBfc2w9kmF

If the trade does not go as expected, the one who is using x100 leverage will be liquidated much sooner. 

His margin is not enough to cover a larger loss and as a result the liquidation price is much closer.

(3/6) 🧵

Let's take this example;

$1000 with x1 leverage = $1000 position size
$10 with x100 leverage = $1000 position size

Even if you think the trader who uses x100 is crazy and the one using x1 is boring, the position size is the same, so both will have the same profit.

(2/6) 🧵

When you talk about leverage you show how little you know about trading.

Leverage is irrelevant, position size is all that matters.  This is why:
